{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517012"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:49:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:49:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12740"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12740"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.07,0.06,0.78,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5195"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55750"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5195"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41294"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10007"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10516"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42806"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55750"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-hour onset of a severe headache. The pain is localised to the top of his head, without radiation elsewhere. He does not have any other symptoms, specifically no double vision, dizziness, nausea or vomiting. There is no phonophobia or photophobia. He has never had a headache like this before. His blood pressure is 144/90 mmHg, pulse 98/min, and temperature 37.2\u00a0\u00b0C. A neurological examination does not show any focal weakness or sensory deficit. There is no nuchal rigidity and his cranial nerves are intact.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["EEG","MRI brain","Cerebral angiogram","CT brain","Lumbar puncture"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen a patient presents to the emergency department with a sudden and severe headache, as in this case, a subarachnoid haemorrhage (SAH) is one of the most concerning potential causes and needs to be excluded. A subarachnoid haemorrhage results from the accumulation of blood between the arachnoid and pia mater.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sudden onset of a severe headache, like in the case described, is a classic symptom of SAH. The most appropriate next intervention is a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the brain\u003C/strong\u003E. A CT scan is a rapid and sensitive imaging modality, particularly effective in detecting acute conditions such as bleeding or masses. The Ottawa SAH rule can be used to identify patients with acute headache who require investigation for SAH. It includes factors such as age 40 years or older, neck pain or stiffness, witnessed loss of consciousness, onset during exertion, thunderclap headache, and limited neck flexion on examination. This patient meets some of these criteria, warranting a CT scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EEEG\u003C/strong\u003E records the brain\u0027s electrical activity and is useful in assessing conditions such as seizures or abnormal brain activity. However, in a patient presenting with a sudden severe headache without other neurological symptoms, EEG is not the initial diagnostic tool of choice. It is more relevant when there is a suspicion of seizures, altered mental status, or other signs of abnormal brain electrical activity, which are not evident in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain\u003C/strong\u003E provides detailed images of the brain and is sensitive for various conditions, including structural abnormalities and tumours. However, in the acute setting, especially when there is a concern for a subarachnoid haemorrhage (SAH) or other urgent intracranial pathology, CT is often preferred due to its rapid availability and sensitivity to blood. If the CT scan is inconclusive, but clinical suspicion remains, an MRI may be considered subsequently for more detailed imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral angiography\u003C/strong\u003E involves injecting contrast into the blood vessels of the brain to visualise them. It is an invasive procedure and is not typically the initial investigation for a patient presenting with a severe headache. Cerebral angiography is usually reserved for cases where vascular abnormalities, such as an aneurysm, are strongly suspected based on other findings. It is not the first-line diagnostic test in the absence of specific indications for vascular imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E involves obtaining cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) for analysis. While lumbar puncture can be a valuable tool in diagnosing certain conditions, it is not the initial step for a patient presenting with a severe headache without other neurological symptoms. In the absence of signs like nausea, vomiting, double vision, or nuchal rigidity, and given the concern for acute intracranial pathology, a CT scan is usually the first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Generally, a non-contrast head CT is obtained on presentation. Almost 99% of cases are picked up on head CT if performed within a 6-hour window.","If the non-contrast head CT is indeterminate or if the patient presents outside of the 6-hour window, a lumbar puncture (LP) is indicated.","The Ottawa SAH rule helps identify patients with acute headache who require investigation for subarachnoid haemorrhage."],"references":["Alwageed HS. Detection of Subarachnoid Hemorrhage in Computed Tomography Using Association Rules Mining. Comput Intell Neurosci. 2022 Aug 31;2022:1133819. doi: 10.1155/2022/1133819. PMID: 36093508; PMCID: PMC9451997.","Kairys N, M Das J, Garg M. Acute Subarachnoid Hemorrhage. [Updated 2022 Oct 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK518975/","Foley RW, Ramachandran S, Akintimehin A, Williams S, Connor SJ, Hart J, Kapadia YK, Timofeev I, Tolias CM, Whyte MB, Kelly PA. Subarachnoid haemorrhage rules in the decision for acute CT of the head: external validation in a UK cohort. Clin Med (Lond). 2021 Mar;21(2):96-100. doi: 10.7861/clinmed.2020-0437. PMID: 33762366; PMCID: PMC8002795."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41294"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12740"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41294"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T20:05:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T09:36:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5195"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55750"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null